Introduction

The dataset is a tidy csv file containing 1599 observations and have 12 variables associated to them. I will perform Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) on a data set which contains red wines with variables on the chemical properties of the wine. I will use visual methods univariate, bivariate and multivariate plots to summarise the main charecteristics of the data set. Main goal here is to find what factors contribute to quality of a red wine .

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

This plot illustrates that there was little to no correlation between wine quality and pH. At the same time, there a trend where more highly rated wines tend to be grouped at higher Citric Acid values. However, the trend is far from definite. There are very highly rated wines at low citric acid values as well as very lowely rated wines at high citric acid values.

Plot Two

Description Two

I think paints the most complete picture of the analysis of wine quality with two takeaways.

Alcohol content has some effect on wine quality rating The effect is not a strong one, and even for a given rating.

This visualization was especially appealing to me because of the way that you can almost see the distribution shuffle from left to right as wine ratings increase. Again, just showing a general tendancy instead of a strong correlation.

Plot Three

Description Three

The citric acid seemed to have the most promeneant effect on wine quality. When plotted against wine quality in a scatter plot like this, only citric acid and alcohol displayed a noticeable trend. In each case, the distribution is slightly skewed towards higher citric acid and higher quality.

Reflection

In this data, my main struggle was to get a higher confidence level when predicting factors that are responsible for the production of different quality of wines especially the ‘Good’ and the ‘Bad’ ones. As the data was very centralized towards the ‘Average’ quality, my training set did not have enough data on the extreme edges to accurately build a model which can predict the quality of a wine given the other variables with lesser margin of error Initially when I was writing and developing for this project, I saw that some wines didn’t have citric acid at all. Also the others showed almost a rectangular distribution. My first thought was maybe this was bad data or incomplete data. But then I researched further about wines. I saw that citric acid actually is added to some wines to increase the acidity. So it’s evident that some wines would not have Citric Acid at all. So actually this was in parallel to my experimental findings.

The other variables showed either a Positively skewed or a Normal Distribution.

First I plotted different variables against the quality to see Univariate relationships between them and then one by one I threw in one or more external factors to see if they together have any effect on the categorical variable. I saw that the factors which affected the quality of the wine the most were Alcohol percentage, Sulphate and Acid concentrations.

I tried to figure out the effect of each individual acid on the overall pH of the wine. Here I found out a very peculiar phenomenon where I saw that for volatile acids, the pH was increasing with acidity which was against everything I learned in my Science classes.

In the final part of my analysis, I plotted multivariate plots to see if there were some interesting combinations of variables which together affected the overall quality of the wine. It was in this section I found out that density did not play a part in improving wine quality.

For future analysis, I would love to have a dataset, where apart from the wine quality, a rank is given for that particular wine by 10 different wine tasters as we know when we include the human element, our opinion changes on so many different factors. So by including the human element in my analysis, I would be able to put in that perspective and see a lot of unseen factors which might result in a better or worse wine quality. Having these factors included inside the dataset would result in a different insight altogether in my analysis.
